'''''Blue Ocean Strategy''''' is a marketing theory from a book published in 2004 which was written by [[W. Chan Kim]] and Renée Mauborgne, professors at [[INSEAD]].{{fact|date=July 2018}}

Based on a study of 150 strategic moves spanning more than a hundred years and thirty industries, Kim and Mauborgne argue that companies can succeed by creating "blue oceans" of uncontested market space, as opposed to "red oceans" where competitors fight for dominance, the analogy being that an ocean full of vicious competition turns red with blood.{{fact|date=July 2018}}

They assert that these strategic moves create a leap in value for the company, its buyers, and its employees while unlocking new demand and making the competition irrelevant. The book presents analytical frameworks and tools to foster an organization's ability to systematically create and capture blue oceans.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Kim, W.C. |author2=Mauborgne, R. |title=Blue Ocean Strategy: How to Create Uncontested Market Space and Make the Competition Irrelevant|year=2004|publisher=Harvard Business School Press|location=Boston|isbn=978-1591396192}}</ref> The expanded edition of Blue Ocean Strategy was published in February, 2015.{{fact|date=July 2018}}

== Book layout and concepts ==
The book is divided into three parts:{{fact|date=July 2018}}
as the other scenarios differ from those mentioned below would be an entirely separate story vice versa.{{fact|date=July 2018}}

1. The first part presents key concepts of blue ocean strategy, including Value Innovation – the simultaneous pursuit of differentiation and low cost – and key analytical tools and frameworks such as the strategy canvas and the four actions framework. The four actions framework aids in eliminating the trade-off between differentiation and low cost within a company. The four actions framework consists of the following:{{fact|date=July 2018}}

*Raise: This questions which factors must be raised within an industry in terms of product, pricing or service standards.
*Eliminate: This questions which areas of a company or industry could be completely eliminated to reduce costs and to create an entirely new market. 
*Reduce: This questions which areas of a company’s product or service are not entirely necessary but play a significant role in your industry, for example, the cost of manufacturing a certain material for a product could be reduced. Therefore, it can be reduced without completely eliminating it. 
*Create: This prompts companies to be innovative with their products. By creating an entirely new product or service, a company can create their own market through differentiation from the competition.<ref name="Blue Ocean Strategy: From Theory to Practice">{{cite journal|last1=Kim|first1=W. Chan|last2=Mauborgne|first2=Renée|title=Blue Ocean Strategy: From Theory to Practice |journal=California Management Review|date=2004|volume=47|issue=3|page=105-121 |doi=10.2307/41166308 |url=http://cmr.ucpress.edu/content/47/3/105 |accessdate=May 10, 2017}}</ref>

2. The second part describes the four principles of blue ocean strategy formulation. These four formulation principles address how an organization can create blue oceans by looking across the six conventional boundaries of competition (Six Paths Framework), reduce their planning risk by following the four steps of visualizing strategy, create new demand by unlocking the three tiers of noncustomers and launch a commercially viable blue ocean idea by aligning unprecedented utility of an offering with strategic pricing and target costing and by overcoming adoption hurdles. The book uses many examples across industries to demonstrate how to break out of traditional competitive (structuralist) strategic thinking and to grow demand and profits for the company and the industry by using blue ocean (reconstructionist) strategic thinking. The four principles are:
# how to create uncontested market space by reconstructing market boundaries,
# focusing on the big picture,
# reaching beyond existing demand and supply in new market spaces 
# getting the strategic sequence right.
3. The third and final part describes the two key implementation principles of blue ocean strategy including tipping point leadership and fair process. These implementation principles are essential for leaders to overcome the four key organizational hurdles that can prevent even the best strategies from being executed. The four key hurdles comprise the cognitive, resource, motivational and political hurdles that prevent people involved in strategy execution from understanding the need to break from status quo, finding the resources to implement the new strategic shift, keeping your people committed to implementing the new strategy, and from overcoming the powerful vested interests that may block the change.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://flevy.com/blue-ocean-strategy|title=Blue Ocean Strategy Overview|publisher=Flevy|accessdate=20 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.technoparktoday.com/blue-ocean-strategy/|title=Blue Ocean Strategy|last=Kumar|first=Ajay S.|publisher=TechnoparkToday.com|accessdate=20 November 2012}}</ref>

===Proposition===
In the book the authors draw the attention of their readers towards the correlation of success stories across industries and the formulation of strategies that provide a solid base to create unconventional success – a strategy termed as "blue ocean strategy". Unlike the "red ocean strategy", the conventional approach to business of beating competition derived from the military organization, the "blue ocean strategy" tries to align innovation with utility, price and cost positions. The book mocks at the phenomena of conventional choice between product/service differentiation and lower cost, but rather suggests that both differentiation and lower costs are achievable simultaneously.{{fact|date=July 2018}}

The authors ask readers "What is the best unit of analysis of profitable growth? Company? Industry?" – a fundamental question without which any strategy for profitable growth is not worthwhile. The authors justify with original and practical ideas that neither the company nor the industry is the best unit of analysis of profitable growth; rather it is the strategic move that creates "blue ocean" and sustained high performance. The book examines the experience of companies in areas as diverse as watches, wine, cement, computers, automobiles, textiles, coffee makers, airlines, retailers, and even the circus, to answer this fundamental question and builds upon the argument about "value innovation" being the cornerstone of a blue ocean strategy. Value innovation is necessarily the alignment of innovation with utility, price and cost positions. This creates uncontested market space and makes competition irrelevant. The new chapters in the expanded edition of the book deal with the issues of how to develop and align the three strategy propositions of value, profit and people, how to sustain and renew blue ocean strategy at both the business level and the corporate level, and how to avoid red ocean traps that keep organizations anchored in existing market space even as they attempt to create new market space.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Allen|first1=Nathen|title=‘Blue Ocean Strategy’ Surges in Schools|url=http://poetsandquantsforexecs.com/2015/05/12/blue-ocean-strategy-surges-through-b-schools/|website=Poets & Quants for Executives}}</ref> The following section discusses the concept behind the book in detail.{{fact|date=July 2018}}

== Concept ==
{{Original research section|date=December 2017}}
[[File:Dralion-Vienna.jpg|thumb|[[Cirque du Soleil]] – an example of creating a new market space, by blending opera and ballet with the circus format while eliminating star performers and animals.]]

The metaphor of red and blue oceans describes the market universe.{{fact|date=July 2018}}

Red oceans represent all the industries in existence today – the known market space. In the red oceans, industry boundaries are defined and accepted, and the competitive rules of the game are known. Here companies try to outperform their rivals to grab a greater share of product or service demand. As the market space gets crowded, prospects for profits and growth are reduced. Products become [[commodities]] or [[Niche market|niche]], and cutthroat competition turns the ocean bloody; hence, the term "red oceans".<ref name="BOS">{{cite web
|url = http://www.insead.edu/alumni/newsletter/February2005/Interview.pdf
|year = 2004
|accessdate = 2008-12-31
|title = A conversation with W.Chan Kim and Renee Mauborgne
|publisher = [[INSEAD]]
|deadurl = yes
|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20081203070029/http://www.insead.edu/alumni/newsletter/February2005/Interview.pdf
|archivedate = 2008-12-03
|df = 
}}</ref>

Blue oceans, in contrast, denote all the industries not in existence today – the unknown market space, untainted by competition. In blue oceans, demand is created rather than fought over. There is ample opportunity for growth that is both profitable and rapid. In blue oceans, competition is irrelevant because the rules of the game are waiting to be set. Blue ocean is an analogy to describe the wider, deeper potential of market space that is not yet explored.<ref name="BOS"/>

The cornerstone of blue ocean strategy is "value innovation", a concept originally outlined in Kim & Mauborgne's 1997 article "Value Innovation - The Strategic Logic of High Growth".<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Kim, W.C. |author2=Mauborgne, R. |title=Value Innovation – The Strategic Logic of High Growth|journal=Harvard Business Review|date=January–February 1997|volume=75|pages=103–112|url=http://hbr.org/2004/07/value-innovation-the-strategic-logic-of-high-growth/ar/1}}</ref> Value innovation is the simultaneous pursuit of differentiation and low cost, creating value for both the buyer, the company, and its employees, thereby opening up new and uncontested market space. The aim of value innovation, as articulated in the article, is not to compete, but to make the competition irrelevant by changing the playing field of strategy. The strategic move must raise and create value for the market, while simultaneously reducing or eliminating features or services that are less valued by the current or future market. The Four Actions Framework is used to help create value innovation and break the value-cost trade-off.  Value innovation challenges [[Michael Porter]]'s idea that successful businesses are either low-cost providers or niche-players.  Instead, blue ocean strategy proposes finding value that crosses conventional [[market segmentation]] and offering value ''and'' lower cost. Educator Charles W. L. Hill proposed a similar idea in 1988 and claimed that Porter's model was flawed because differentiation can be a means for firms to achieve low cost. He proposed that a combination of differentiation and low cost might be necessary for firms to achieve a sustainable competitive advantage.{{fact|date=July 2018}}

Many others have proposed similar strategies. For example, Swedish educators [[Jonas Ridderstråle]] and [[Kjell Nordström]] in their 1999 book ''[[Funky Business]]'' follow a similar line of reasoning. For example, "competing factors" in blue ocean strategy are similar to the definition of "finite and infinite dimensions" in ''Funky Business''. Just as blue ocean strategy claims that a red ocean strategy does not guarantee success, ''Funky Business'' explained that "Competitive Strategy is the route to nowhere". ''Funky Business'' argues that firms need to create "sensational strategies". Just like blue ocean strategy, a sensational strategy is about "playing a different game" according to Ridderstråle and Nordström. Ridderstråle and Nordström also claim that the aim of companies is to create temporary monopolies. Kim and Mauborgne explain that the aim of companies is to create blue oceans, that will eventually turn red. This is the same idea expressed in the form of an analogy. Ridderstråle and Nordström also claimed in 1999 that "in the slow-growth 1990s overcapacity is the norm in most businesses". Kim and Mauborgne claim that blue ocean strategy makes sense in a world where supply exceeds demand.{{fact|date=July 2018}}

=== Blue ocean vs. red ocean ===
Kim and Mauborgne argue that while traditional competition-based strategies (red ocean strategies) are necessary, they are not sufficient to sustain high performance. Companies need to go beyond competing. To seize new profit and growth opportunities they also need to create blue oceans. The authors argue that competition based strategies assume that an industry's structural conditions are given and that firms are forced to compete within them, an assumption based on what academics call the structuralist view, or environmental determinism. To sustain themselves in the marketplace, practitioners of red ocean strategy focus on building advantages over the competition, usually by assessing what competitors do and striving to do it better. Here, grabbing a bigger share of the market is seen as a [[zero-sum game]] in which one company's gain is achieved at another company’s loss. Hence, competition, the supply side of the equation, becomes the defining variable of strategy. Here, cost and value are seen as trade-offs and a firm chooses a distinctive cost or differentiation position. Because the total profit level of the industry is also determined by structural factors, firms principally seek to capture and redistribute wealth instead of creating wealth. They focus on dividing up the red ocean, where growth is increasingly limited.{{fact|date=July 2018}}

Blue ocean strategy, on the other hand, is based on the view that market boundaries and industry structure are not given and can be reconstructed by the actions and beliefs of industry players. This is what the authors call ''the reconstructionist view''. Assuming that structure and market boundaries exist only in managers’ minds, practitioners who hold this view do not let existing market structures limit their thinking. To them, extra demand is out there, largely untapped. The crux of the problem is how to create it. This, in turn, requires a shift of attention from supply to demand, from a focus on competing to a focus on ''value innovation'' – that is, the creation of innovative value to unlock new demand. This is achieved via the simultaneous pursuit of differentiation and low-cost. As market structure is changed by breaking the value/cost tradeoff, so are the rules of the game. Competition in the old game is therefore rendered irrelevant. By expanding the demand side of the economy, new wealth is created. Such a strategy therefore allows firms to largely play a non–zero-sum game, with high payoff possibilities.{{fact|date=July 2018}}

== Examples ==

===Examples documented in the book===

Some examples of companies that may have created new market spaces in the opinion of Kim and Mauborgne include:{{fact|date=July 2018}}
* [[Cirque du Soleil]]: Blending of opera and ballet with circus format while eliminating star performer and animals;
* [[Netjets]]: fractional jet ownership;
* [[Southwest Airlines]]: offering flexibility of bus travel at the speed of air travel using secondary airports;
* [[Curves International|Curves]]: redefining market boundaries between health clubs and home exercise programs for women;
* [[Home Depot]]: offering the prices and range of [[lumber yard]], while offering consumers classes to help them with [[DIY]] projects;
* [[Dyson (company)|Dyson]]: [[Cyclonic_separation|Cyclonic]] [[Vacuum Cleaners]].

===Recent application examples===

Reports of businesses using blue ocean strategy concepts include:{{fact|date=July 2018}}

* [[China Mobile]]: China Mobile CEO Wang Jianzhou talked about China's hinterland as a classic "blue-ocean market," where the company is casting its net widely without worrying about getting tangled up with the nets of rivals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/2007/08/06/100156748/index2.htm|title=China's mobile maestro (pg. 2) - August 6, 2007|first=By Clay Chandler, Fortune senior|last=writer|website=money.cnn.com}}</ref>
* [[Pitney Bowes]]: Michael Critelli, the departing CEO of Pitney Bowes, explained how Pitney Bowes created the Advanced Concept & Technology Group (ACTG), a unit responsible for identifying and developing new products outside. Critelli cited ACTG's development of a machine, which enables people to design and print their own postage from their desktops, as an example of a blue ocean strategic move.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldbusinesslive.com/search/article/655150/wb-interview-michael-critelli/|title=World Business Interview: Michael Critelli, 9 May 2007|publisher=}}</ref>
* [[Starwood Hotels and Resorts Worldwide]]: In an interview to INSEAD Knowledge, Robyn Pratt, Vice President, Six Sigma and Operational Innovation, talks about how Starwood is taking a step-by-step approach to implementing the concept.<ref>INSEAD Knowledge: The Starwood experience {{cite web |url=http://knowledge.insead.edu/contents/starwood.cfm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-02-06 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080220014348/http://knowledge.insead.edu/contents/starwood.cfm |archivedate=2008-02-20 |df= }}</ref>
*[[Wii]]: Rather than releasing a more technologically advanced video game console with more features as in previous generations, Nintendo released a console with innovative controls made to attract populations that are typically excluded from the target demographic for video games, such as the elderly.<ref>{{cite news|last=Williams|first=Mike|title=Nintendo's Iwata Doesn't Fear Failure|url=http://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2013-10-10-nintendos-iwata-doesnt-fear-failure|newspaper=Gamesindustry|date=October 10, 2013}}</ref>
*[[TATA Motors]]: With its recent product, the [[Tata Nano|Nano car]], the company has adopted a combination of differentiation and low cost.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Kim, W.C. |author2=Mauborgne, R. |author3=Bong, R. |author4=Ji, M. |title=Tata Nano: The People’s Car That Promises to Reconstruct the Automobile Industry|url=http://cb.hbsp.harvard.edu/cb/web/product_detail.seam?E=4837562&R=INS262-PDF-ENG&conversationId=1840411|work=Harvard Business School Press |accessdate=May 10, 2017}}</ref>
*[[Starbucks]]: Starbucks entered a historically crowded marketplace, the coffee shop industry; however, it found its way to success through the blue ocean strategy. Starbucks separated itself from the competition by combining differentiation, low cost and a customer-oriented approach from the beginning of its operation. Starbucks also focused on maximizing its brand’s exposure, rather than solely focusing on itself as just another coffee shop. In terms of differentiation, Starbucks offered a variety of products, such as smoothies, teas and coffees that no other establishment was offering. By training specialised staff, the company operated with less staff than would usually be needed. Starbuck also championed professionalism and excellent customer service, for example, offering personalised coffee cups. To enhance the customer experience, Starbucks changed the furnishings in their stores, creating a comfortable environment that persuades their customers to spend more time in store.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=TĂLPĂU|first1=A.|last2=BOŞCOR|first2=D.|title=CUSTOMER-ORIENTED MARKETING - A STRATEGY THAT GUARANTEES SUCCESS: STARBUCKS AND MCDONALD’S|journal=Bulletin of the Transilvania University Basov|date=2011|volume=4|issue=1|page=51-61|url=https://syokotablog.wordpress.com/2016/05/26/customer-oriented-marketing-a-strategy-that-guarantees-success-starbucks-and-mcdonalds/ |accessdate=May 10, 2017}}</ref>

==Reception==
Since ''Blue Ocean Strategy'' was published in 2005 it has been translated into 43 languages and has sold over 3.5 million copies. The book was named a bestseller by the Wall Street Journal, BusinessWeek, and Amazon.com.<ref>{{cite news|title=Best Selling Books|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=March 4, 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The BusinessWeek Best Seller List|url=http://www.businessweek.com/pdfs/2007/0745_bestsellers.pdf|accessdate=March 17, 2014|newspaper=BusinessWeek|date=November 5, 2007|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150508195033/http://www.businessweek.com/pdfs/2007/0745_bestsellers.pdf|archivedate=May 8, 2015|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Best Books of 2005|url=https://www.amazon.com/gp/feature.html/ref=br_lf_m_593614_pglink_2?ie=UTF8&docId=593614&plgroup=1&plpage=2|work=Amazon.com|accessdate=March 17, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Blue Ocean Strategy: How to Create Uncontested Market Space and Make the Competition Irrelevant|url=https://www.amazon.ca/Blue-Ocean-Strategy-Uncontested-Competition/dp/1591396190|work=Amazon.com|accessdate=March 17, 2014}}</ref> It was selected as one of the “Best Books of 2005” by Fast Company magazine, won “The Best Business Book of 2005” Prize at the Frankfurt Book Fair, and achieved bestselling book of the decade status by 800-CEO-READ (2000-2010).<ref>{{cite news|last=Lidsky|first=David|title=Fast Company's Best Books of 2005|url=http://www.fastcompany.com/673561/fast-companys-best-books-2005|accessdate=March 17, 2014|newspaper=Fast Company|date=January 5, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Murray|first=Patricia|title=Business - Widen Your Horizons - How to... Out-think Your Competition Rather Than Trying to Outdo Other's Offers or Products, Re-define the Market, Writes Patricia Murray|newspaper=Sunday Tribune|date=December 17, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=800-CEO-READ's Decade-in-Review|url=http://blog.800ceoread.com/?s=blue+ocean+strategy|work=800ceoread|accessdate=March 17, 2014}}</ref> Strategy+Business magazine selected it as #1 strategy book of 2005.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lucier|first=Chuck|title=Best Business Books 2005: Strategy|url=http://www.strategy-business.com/article/05409c|work=strategy+business|accessdate=March 17, 2014}}</ref>

In 2009, ''Blue Ocean Strategy'' was selected by the China Daily and the China Research Institute as one of the 40 most influential books in the History of the People's Republic of China (1949-2009) along with Adam Smith’s ″The Wealth of Nations″ under the category of ″Economics and Finance.″<ref>{{cite web|title=独家发布：新中国60年中国最具影响力的600本书|url=http://book.ifeng.com/psl/sh/200909/0930_3556_1371290_15.shtml|work=ifeng.com|accessdate=March 17, 2014|date=September 30, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title="新中国60年中国最具影响力的600本书"名单|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/book/2009-09/29/content_12125264.htm|work=www.news.cn|accessdate=March 17, 2014|date=September 29, 2009}}</ref>  In 2010, Polish group ThinkTank selected ''Blue Ocean Strategy'' as one of the Top 20 books that have shaped Polish Leaders.<ref>{{cite web|title=TOP20 Książek, Które Ukształtowały Polskich Liderów|url=http://kariera.pb.pl/3195759,30700,top20-ksiazek-ktore-uksztaltowaly-polskich-liderow|work=Puls Biznesu|accessdate=March 17, 2014}}</ref>  ''Blue Ocean Strategy'' won the Thinkers50 2011 Strategy Award for Best Business Book of the decade and in the same year, it was introduced to the Fast Company Leadership Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite web|title=W. Chan Kim & Renee Mauborgne|url=http://www.thinkers50.com/biographies/w-chan-kim-renee-mauborgne/|work=Thinkers50|accessdate=March 17, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Ohannessian|first=Kevin|title=The Leadership Hall of Fame|url=http://www.fastcompany.com/1801015/leadership-hall-fame|accessdate=March 17, 2014|newspaper=Fast Company|date=December 26, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Ohannessian|first=Kevin|title=Leadership Hall of Fame: W. Chan Kim and Renee Mauborgne, Authors of "Blue Ocean Strategy"|url=http://www.fastcompany.com/1769549/leadership-hall-fame-w-chan-kim-and-ren%C3%A9e-mauborgne-authors-blue-ocean-strategy|accessdate=March 17, 2014|newspaper=Fast Company|date=July 28, 2011}}</ref> In 2013, the book received the GoodBooks Award in the Management category by the Vietnamese Institute for Research on Education Development (IRED), was selected as one of the 15 Best Business Books of the last decade in Russia by the Kommersant.ru magazine, and selected as one of the top three best management books in Japan by the Diamond Harvard Business Review.<ref>{{cite web|title='Nắng tháng 8', 'Biển và chim bói cá' đoạt giải Sách hay 2013|url=http://vietbao.vn/Van-hoa/Nang-thang-8-Bien-va-chim-boi-ca-doat-giai-Sach-hay-2013/22141426/181/|work=VietBao|accessdate=March 18, 2014|date=September 22, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Fukolova|first=Julia|title=Bestseller of all times|url=http://www.kommersant.ru/doc/2079220|work=kommersant.ru|accessdate=March 21, 2014|date=December 3, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Harvard Business Review Readers Choose the Best Management Books 2013|url=http://www.dhbr.net/articles/-/2124|work=Diamond Harvard Business Review|accessdate=March 18, 2014|date=October 8, 2013}}</ref>

The Wall Street Journal recommends ''Blue Ocean Strategy'' for the top manager.<ref>{{cite news|title=In the Lead Forum|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=April 16, 2007|page=R2}}</ref> Forbes calls it one of the ten business trends for 2013 and argues that "blue ocean strategies are more influential than ever."<ref>{{cite news|last=Simon|first=Andrea|title=Ten Business Trends From The Trenches For 2013|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/womensmedia/2013/02/11/ten-business-trends-from-the-trenches-for-2013/|accessdate=March 18, 2014|newspaper=Forbes|date=November 2, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Simon|first=Andrea|title=Major Mid-Year Correction Necessary|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/womensmedia/2013/06/18/major-mid-year-correction-necessary/|accessdate=March 19, 2014|newspaper=Forbes|date=June 18, 2013}}</ref> BusinessWeek says that "''Blue Ocean Strategy'' will have you wondering why companies need so much persuasion to stay out of shark-infested waters."<ref>{{cite news |title=Blue Ocean Strategy <!--|accessdate=March 18, 2014-->|newspaper=BusinessWeek|date=April 4, 2005}}</ref> The Business Strategy Review said the book "challenges everything you knew about strategy", and the Business Times called on firms to "adopt blue ocean strategy to stay ahead."<ref>{{cite journal|last=Dearlove|first=Des|author-link=Des Dearlove|title=Forever Blue|journal=Business Strategy Review|date=Spring 2005|pages=56–59|url=http://bsr.london.edu/files/257/forever-blue.pdf%E2%80%8E}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Huifen|first=Chen|title=Firms Should Adopt Blue Ocean Strategy to Stay Ahead|newspaper=The Business Times|date=October 13, 2004}}</ref>  Marketplace magazine recommends ''Blue Ocean Strategy'' as a book "you need to read."<ref>{{cite news|last=Lilly|first=Bryan|title=Explore New Markets With Seaworthy Strategy|newspaper=Marketplace Magazine|date=September 5, 2005}}</ref>  In addition, the book has received many positive reviews from various publications that include Chicago Tribune, Daily Herald, Credit Union Journal, Vancouver Sun, Association Meetings, Strategy & Leadership, and Business First, among many others.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pawlak|first=Jim|title=The Edge. New Book|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=January 31, 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Pawlak|first=Jim|title=Companies Hope to Sail in Profitable Blue Ocean|newspaper=Daily Herald|date=January 31, 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Barlett|first=Michael|title=Attention Next Generation! Do You Have the Passion?|newspaper=Credit Union Journal|date=November 14, 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Gismondi|first=Anthony|title=Yellowtail, Spain, Scretowps -- 2004's Top Wine Stories|newspaper=Vancouver Sun|date=January 1, 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=McGee|first=Regina|title=What's Up with Blue Ocean Buzz?|newspaper=Association Meetings|date=October 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Abraham|first=Stan|title=Blue Oceans, Temporary Monopolies, and Lessons from Practice|journal=Strategy & Leadership|date=October 1, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The Top 10 Business Books for April|newspaper=Business First|date=May 18, 2007}}</ref>

== Criticisms ==
While Kim and Mauborgne propose approaches to finding uncontested market space, at the present there are few success stories of companies that have actively applied their theories. One success story that does exist is [[Nintendo]], who first applied the blue ocean strategy to create the [[Nintendo DS]] [[handheld game system]] which was the first portable gaming system to offer dual-screen gaming and a [[touch screen]] in 2004. In 2006, Nintendo released the [[Wii]], which used unique motion controls. The [[3DS]] is Nintendo's third endeavour for its blue ocean strategy. Its first two attempts, the Nintendo DS and Wii, were wildly successful, becoming some of the biggest selling platforms in history. Nintendo revealed their Blue Ocean Strategy during an E3 press conference during the hype build-up of the Wii.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}

However, with just one case study, this hole in their data persists despite the publication of value innovation concepts dating back to 1997. Hence, a critical question is whether this book and its related ideas are ''descriptive'' rather than ''prescriptive.''<ref name="CMO">{{cite news | last = Pollard | first = Wayne E. | title = Blue Ocean Strategy's Fatal Flaw | publisher = CMO Magazine | date = 2004-12-01}}</ref>  The authors present many examples of successful innovations, and then explain from their Blue Ocean perspective – essentially interpreting success through their lenses.<ref name="twoscenarios">{{cite web| url=http://twoscenarios.typepad.com/maneuver_marketing_commun/blue_ocean_strategy/index.html | title=Multiple Critiques of Blue Ocean Strategy | year = 2007 | accessdate=2007-07-19}}</ref>

The research process followed by the authors has been criticized on several grounds.<ref name="twoscenarios" /> Criticisms include claims that no [[control group]] was used, that there is no way to know how many companies using a blue ocean strategy failed and the theory is thus [[falsifiability|unfalsifiable]], that a [[Deductive reasoning|deductive]] process was not followed, and that the examples in the book were selected to "tell a winning story".{{Citation needed|date=May 2009}}

Additionally, blue ocean strategy cannot be identified as true causation for success. The authors cite the strategies used by NYPD Commissioner Bratton as a key example of Blue Ocean applied in the public sector. They defined this success as a significant drop in crime in the City of New York after Bratton took office in 1994. Many social scientists would disagree that it was Bratton's policies that led to crime reduction: rather, the city was simply part of a nationwide trend in decreasing crime.{{fact|date=July 2018}}

Brand and communication are taken for granted and do not represent a key for success. Kim and Maubourgne take the marketing of a value innovation as a given, assuming the marketing success will come as a matter of course.<ref name="CMO"/>

It is argued that rather than a theory, blue ocean strategy is an extremely successful attempt to [[Brand management|brand]] a set of already existing concepts and frameworks with a highly "sticky" idea.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.ribbonfarm.com/2007/08/06/book-review-blue-ocean-strategy/ | title=Critique of Blue Ocean Strategy | year = 2007 | accessdate=2011-06-30}}</ref> The blue ocean/red ocean analogy is a powerful and memorable metaphor, which is responsible for its popularity. This metaphor can be powerful enough to stimulate people to action. However, the concepts behind the Blue Ocean Strategy (such as the competing factors, the [[Consumer behaviour|consumer]] cycle, non-customers, etc.) are not new. Many of these tools are also used by [[Six Sigma]] practitioners and proposed by other [[List of business theorists|management theorists]].{{fact|date=July 2018}}

Many of the book's key concepts were previously covered in ''Competing For The Future'' by [[Gary Hamel]] and [[C.K. Prahalad]], which was published in 1996.<ref name=CultStrat>{{cite book |last=Holt|first=Douglas |last2=Cameron |first2=Douglas |year=2010 |title=Cultural Strategy |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-958740-7}}</ref> The authors encouraged managers to stake out new marketing space, which they termed ''white space'', in order to "create and dominate emerging opportunities".<ref name=CultStrat />

