[[Image:Symantechq 2011.jpg|thumb|250px|Symantec's headquarters in Mountain View, California.]]
[[Symantec]] is an American [[computer software]] company founded on March 1, 1982.<ref name="mania">{{cite news|work=[[San Jose Mercury News]]|date=1987-10-12|title=Merger Mania Strikes Software Industry}}</ref> It is an [[international corporation]] that specializes in selling [[security]] and [[information management]] software,<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-04-25|url= http://www.informationweek.com/update-symantec-to-acquire-veritas-for-$135-billion/d/d-id/1029104 |title=UPDATE: Symantec To Acquire Veritas For $13.5 Billion  |work=[[InformationWeek]]|date=2004-12-16|author=Hulme, George V.|author2=Foley, John  }}</ref> and is listed on the [[NASDAQ-100]] stock market index and [[Fortune 1000]] list of the largest American companies.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[Business Wire]]|date=2006-09-12|title=SilverBack Appoints VP of Global Sales and VP of Product Marketing; Peter Klanian & Jonathan Wolf Named to Join Executive Team.}}</ref> [[Gary Hendrix]] founded the company in 1982 with the help of a [[National Science Foundation]] grant. Symantec was originally focused on [[artificial intelligence]]-related projects, and Hendrix hired several [[Stanford University]] [[natural language processing]] researchers as the company's first employees.<ref>{{cite book|title= International Directory of Company Histories|volume=10|publisher=St. James Press|year=1995}}</ref> After the company's [[initial public offering]] in 1989, Hendrix left the company in 1991 and moved to [[Texas]].<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-11-01|url=http://archive.computerhistory.org/resources/text/Oral_History/Hendrix_Gary/Hendrix_Gary.oral_history.2004.102657945.pdf|title= Oral History of Gary Hendrix  PDF Document |publisher=Computer History Museum|date=2004-11-19|author=Spicer, Dag|format=PDF}}</ref> The company has acquired 57 companies, purchased stakes in 2 firms, and divested 26 companies, in which parts of the company are sold to another company. Of the companies that Symantec has acquired, 50 were based in the United States. Symantec has not released the financial details for most of these mergers and acquisitions.

Symantec's first acquisition was C&E Software on January 1, 1984, and the founder of C&E Software, [[Gordon Eubanks]], became the new [[chief executive officer]] of Symantec.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-10-30 |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=/chronicle/archive/1999/04/07/BU45281.DTL |title=Symantec Chair Will Become CEO of Oblix |work=San Francisco Chronicle |date=1999-04-07 |author=Evangelista, Benny |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030217185345/http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=%2Fchronicle%2Farchive%2F1999%2F04%2F07%2FBU45281.DTL |archivedate=February 17, 2003 |df= }}</ref> The company has made three acquisitions with a value greater than $1&nbsp;billion: [[VeriSign]] was acquired on May 19, 2010 for $1.250 billion, [[Altiris]] was acquired on April 6, 2007 for $1.038&nbsp;billion, and Symantec purchased [[Veritas Software]] on July 2, 2005 for $13&nbsp;billion. The deal with Veritas was Symantec's largest acquisition and made Symantec the fifth-largest software company in the world.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-10-30|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E00E5DD163AF936A15755C0A9639C8B63|title= Shareholders Approve Symantec-Veritas Software Merger  |work=The New York Times|date=2005-06-25|author=Flynn, Laurie J. }}</ref> The company made the most acquisitions in 2004 with six: [[ON Technology]], [[Brightmail]], [[TurnTide]], [[@stake]], [[LIRIC Associates]], and [[Platform Logic]].

